"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869586","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Government does not approve trials of automated vehicle technology. As set out in the UK Code of Practice, developers can carry out trials if they are conducted in line with UK law. The Code does not specify what technology should or should not be used as part of a trial.</p><p> </p><p>Around a dozen current publicly funded projects will be undertaking trials on automated vehicles up to 2021. The vehicles, in general, have a combination of sensor types, for example vision, radar, sonar and/or lidar, to suit the needs of the environmental conditions and use case. The Government does not stipulate what sensor suites projects should use. It is up to project partners to demonstrate what suite will safely deliver on road trials in line with current road traffic law, as highlighted in the UK Code of Practice.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-04-03T13:53:52.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869586/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869586/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869586/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-22","Driverless Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether any autonomous or semi-autonomous driving trials have been approved for public roads in the UK, using purely optical cameras or radar, without LIDAR systems.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL6591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869587","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Government is not aware of any UK trials involving automated vehicles that have resulted in injuries. There are already requirements to report collisions in current road traffic law, so developers must comply with those requirements.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-04-03T13:53:02.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869587/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869587/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869587/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-22","Driverless Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether there have been any injuries incurred during autonomous or semi-autonomous driving trials in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL6592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869588","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-03","<p>The UK’s Code of Practice provides guidance on testing automated vehicle technologies on public roads or in other public places in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>The Government does not approve trials of automated vehicle technology that are carried out in line with the current UK Code of Practice. It is for manufacturers to ensure they are taking appropriate steps to ensure their trials comply with the law.</p><p> </p><p>Information about the trials that are being co-funded by Government is available as a booklet entitled “UK Connected and Autonomous Vehicle Research and Development Projects 2017” online. A copy of the booklet is attached for ease of reference.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-04-03T13:54:29.343Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869588/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869588/answer","CCAV - Research and Development Projects 2017.pdf","CCAV Research and Development Projects 2017","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869588/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-22","Driverless Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they will list (1) all autonomous or semi-autonomous driving trials approved in the UK, and (2) any approved on public roads.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL6593"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869589","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Tesla Model 3 has not received type approval from the Vehicle Certification Agency, which is the UK’s Type Approval Authority.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-04-03T13:50:21.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869589/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869589/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869589/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-22","Electric Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the TESLA model 3 has received type approval in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL6594"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869590","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-03","<p>The Tesla Model 3 has not undergone any safety or environmental tests in the UK as would be required for the Vehicle Certification Agency to issue a European Whole Vehicle Type Approval (ECWVTA), or an Individual Vehicle Approval (IVA) certificate.</p><p><br>Testing could be undertaken by other EU Type Approval Authorities but the Department for Transport would only become aware of such testing when the type approval certificate is issued, or when the vehicle manufacturer seeks first registration in the UK.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg",,"2018-04-03T13:48:40.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869590/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869590/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869590/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-22","Electric Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether the TESLA model 3 has undergone safety tests applicable for use in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL6595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869591","Department for Transport","false","2018-04-03","<p>The UK Code of Practice, published in July 2015, sets out that developers can carry out trials of automated vehicle technology if they are conducted in line with UK law. This includes having: 1) a safety driver (in or out of the vehicle) who is ready, able, and willing to resume control of the vehicle; 2) a roadworthy vehicle; and 3) appropriate insurance. The Code makes it clear that it is for developers to assure themselves that they are complying with the law and conducting trials safely.</p><p> </p><p>The Government plans to update the Code of Practice in Summer 2018, to provide guidance to support true self-driving tests. We are working to develop an application process, with assessments being made on a case by case basis.</p>",,"Baroness Sugg","HL6612","2018-04-03T13:52:34.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869591/answer","Biography information for Baroness Sugg","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869591/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869591/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-22","Driverless Vehicles","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is the regulatory and safety assessment process before autonomous or semi-autonomous driving trials can be permitted on public roads in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Goss Moor",,"Lord Taylor of Goss Moor","HL6596"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869592","Department for Exiting the European Union ","false","2018-03-29","<p>There is a dedicated page on the GOV.UK website, <em>UK nationals in the EU: Essential Information</em>. This page is regularly updated and provides the latest information and guidance on how the UK’s exit from the EU might impact on UK nationals living in the EU. The page also includes detail of the citizens’ rights agreement, which will provide UK nationals with more certainty about residence, healthcare, pensions and other benefits.<br><br></p><p>The Government is also using other communication channels to engage with UK nationals in the EU, reaching out to UK nationals at meetings, events and online. Ministers from the Department for Exiting the European Union have met delegates from groups representing UK nationals in the EU, to hear their concerns. Embassies and Ambassadors have also engaged extensively with their communities in country.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Callanan",,"2018-03-29T12:17:23.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869592/answer","Biography information for Lord Callanan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869592/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869592/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union ","Exiting the European Union ","2018-03-22","British Nationals Abroad: EU Countries","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to issue clear guidance on the rights of British nationals living in the EU after Brexit.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL6597"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869593","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-09","<p>The Government is undertaking a wide range of analysis looking at the implications of UK withdrawal from the EU, including the implications for consumers. This programme of analysis is constantly developing and evolving. We continue to engage with a wide range of stakeholders, including consumer organisations, in order to inform our negotiations.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-04-09T15:39:55.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869593/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869593/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869593/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-22","Cost of Living","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they have made any assessment of the effect of Brexit on consumers, particularly regarding its effect on the cost of living.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL6598"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869594","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-09","<p>Ministers regularly meet small and medium sized enterprises (SMEs) and their representative bodies, as part of our preparation to leave the EU, to understand the concerns of small business owners and to find out what support they want from government.</p><p> </p><p>The time-limited implementation period responds to many of their concerns by giving businesses and citizens across the European Union and United Kingdom time they need to prepare for the future, by ensuring our access to each other’s markets continues on current terms.</p><p> </p><p>The support provided to businesses will also be informed by the outcome of negotiations with the EU on our future relationship.</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-04-09T15:39:26.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869594/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869594/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869594/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-22","Business","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they consider that the recently agreed transition period will provide enough time for businesses to be ready for Brexit; and what support they will provide, particularly to smaller businesses, to ensure that they are.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL6599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869595","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-04","<p>We are aware that some UK processed food exports contain a high proportion of non-UK content which may have implications for meeting origin rules in trade agreements. The government is currently working with stakeholders to understand business concerns and develop potential solutions to inform the UK’s negotiating approach.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2018-04-04T13:07:39.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869595/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869595/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869595/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-22","Processed Food: UK Trade with EU","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what assessment they have made of the risk that, due to a high proportion of non-UK ingredients, processed foods may be subject to EU tariffs after Brexit; and what steps they plan to take to address the issue.","false","Biography information for Lord Taylor of Warwick",,"Lord Taylor of Warwick","HL6600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869596","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-04-09","<p>The Foreign Secretary repeatedly made it clear that we have no quarrel with the Russian people. The Foreign Secretary's concern was that President Putin could use the World Cup to serve his propaganda aims. Distortion of facts and divergence from the truth is a regular tactic of Putin's Russia. The Government are well aware of the huge sacrifices made by the Russian people during the Second World War, and our shared history in defeating Nazism.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2018-04-09T13:40:33.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869596/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869596/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869596/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-22","Russia: Football","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the remarks by the Foreign Secretary on 21 March comparing the way President Putin is promoting the World Cup in Russia to Hitler's use of the 1936 Berlin Olympics, what assessment they have made of the likely reception of the Foreign Secretary’s words among the Russian population, particularly in the light of that country’s response to Nazism during the Second World War.","false","Biography information for Lord Truscott",,"Lord Truscott","HL6601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869597","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-09","<p>The Government has made clear that its ambition for a close association with the Euratom Community after the UK’s withdrawal from the European Union includes seeking a close association with the Euratom Research and Training Programme, including the Joint European Torus (JET) and the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor (ITER) projects; continuity of open trade arrangements for nuclear goods and products to ensure that the nuclear industry is able to continue to trade across EU borders without disruption; and close and effective cooperation with Euratom on nuclear safety.</p><p>The negotiations on the future relationship between the UK and the EU have not yet begun so no formal meetings have yet taken place on the nature of the future relationship with Euratom. The Government has ensured that the European Commission is aware of the Government’s January Ministerial Statement setting out the UK’s objective of close association on Euratom and what this would cover. This was reinforced in my right hon. Friend the Prime Minister’s speech at Mansion House on 2 March. The Government will continue to report on progress through its quarterly reports to Parliament, the first of which was made on 26 March.</p><p> </p><p> </p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-04-09T15:39:02.987Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869597/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869597/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869597/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-22","EURATOM","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government, further to the remarks by Lord Henley on 20 March (HL Deb, col 219) that they will seek a "close association" with Euratom after Brexit, what areas they seek to cover in such an association; whether they have engaged in (1) meetings, and (2) correspondence, with Euratom about such an association; if not, when they will approach Euratom about such an association; and whether they will report on progress on that issue in the regular reports to Parliament provided for in the Nuclear Safeguards Bill.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6602"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869598","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-04-09","<p>The US has a legal requirement for a nuclear cooperation agreement to be in place before civil nuclear trade with another country can be permitted. For this reason, the Government has prioritised discussions with the US, to ensure that a new bilateral agreement will be in place when Euratom’s agreements no longer apply to the UK. The strong links between US and UK on civil nuclear matters ensure that both parties are keen to progress this agreement to their mutual benefit. Significant progress has been made on the substance of the new agreement and it is on track to be presented to the UK Parliament and US Congress in the course of 2018 for ratification, ensuring that the agreement will be ready well before the end of 2020</p>",,"Lord Henley",,"2018-04-09T15:40:15.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869598/answer","Biography information for Lord Henley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869598/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869598/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-22","Radioactive Materials: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government what is their contingency plan in the event that the United States Senate does not ratify by treaty a new Nuclear Cooperation Agreement by the end of 2020, following the UK's exit from Euratom.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6603"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869599","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-04-09","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring a high level of public health protection is maintained as we exit the European Union. The United Kingdom has a strong public health framework and leads Europe in many aspects of health protection and promotion. As the Secretary of State has set out, the Government’s principles as we exit the EU are that patients are not disadvantaged and patient safety remains at the heart of all we do. The Secretary of State has a statutory duty to take all steps that he considers appropriate to protect the health of the public in England from disease or other dangers to health.</p><p>The UK is also a signatory to, and is bound by, International Health Regulations which set out core capacities for World Health Organization member states, to ‘prevent, protect against, control and provide a public health response to the international spread of disease.’ The UK will also continue cooperation in international forums, such as the World Health Organization.</p>",,"Lord O'Shaughnessy",,"2018-04-09T13:46:31.86Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869599/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Shaughnessy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869599/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/869599/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-22","Public Health: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty's Government whether they intend to ensure that the public health protections available to UK citizens under Article 168 of the Lisbon Treaty will be enshrined in UK law following the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Lord Warner",,"Lord Warner","HL6604"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870179","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-28","<p>Ministers have been in regular contact with the Information Commissioner on this matter.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","904618","2018-03-28T16:03:04.37Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870179/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870179/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870179/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-22","Cambridge Analytica","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport,  what recent discussions he has had with the Information Commissioner on Cambridge Analytica.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","904626"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870180","Department for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","false","2018-03-28","<p>Ministers have been in regular contact with the Information Commissioner on this matter.</p>","Stourbridge","Margot James","904626","2018-03-28T16:03:04.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870180/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870180/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/870180/answer",,,,,"10","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","Digital, Culture, Media and Sport","2018-03-22","Cambridge Analytica","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Digital, Culture, Media and Sport, what recent discussions he has had with the Information Commissioner on Cambridge Analytica.","false","Biography information for Joanna Cherry","Edinburgh South West","Joanna Cherry","904618"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968092","Department for International Trade","false","2018-09-17","<p>As we leave the European Union, we are seeking to replicate our existing EU free trade agreements and other EU preferential arrangements, to ensure continuity in our trade and investment relationships with third countries.</p><p>The Prime Minister and Israeli Prime Minister established a joint trade working group in February 2017. In March 2017, my noble friend, the then Minister of State for Trade Policy (Lord Price CVO), visited Israel to chair the first meeting of the working group, which is continuing to make positive progress towards ensuring a smooth transition.</p><p>Securing continuity will be a strong foundation to build upon our already successful trading relationships after we leave the EU, and we are making good progress.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2018-09-17T13:38:11.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968092/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968092/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/968092/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-22","Overseas Trade: Israel","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what steps he is taking to ensure that the benefits accrued by the UK in trade liberalisation between the EU and Israel are not lost when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Dr Matthew Offord","Hendon","Dr Matthew Offord","170761"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868347","Department for Education","false","2018-03-26","<p>The role and remit of the Social Mobility Commission is set out in legislation. We believe that the Commission under current legislation is able to act as an effective advocate for social mobility, and advise government, educators, employers and others on how best to tackle this important issue. There are no current plans to change the remit of the Commission.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-26T16:42:06.577Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868347/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868347/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868347/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-21","Social Mobility Commission","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what recent assessment he has made of the adequacy of the remit of the Social Mobility Commission; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","133567"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868348","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-26","<p>Disease X is a hypothetical infection used to represent the knowledge that a serious international epidemic could be caused by a pathogen currently unknown to cause human disease.</p><p> </p><p>Public Health England (PHE) has comprehensive systems in place to identify and monitor global outbreaks of infectious disease, including incidents where the cause is not identified or the outbreak is caused by a pathogen currently unknown to cause human disease such as World Health Organization’s hypothetical “Disease X”.</p><p> </p><p>Robust risk assessment processes exist to review threats to the United Kingdom population. As information emerges appropriate mitigation strategies will be implemented to protect the health of the UK public. The PHE National Emergency Response plans exist to deal with such event and have cross-Government agreement.</p><p> </p><p>The National Health Service-PHE High Consequence Infectious Disease (HCID) programme, initiated after the Ebola outbreak, has developed clinical and public health protocols and plans to provide a resilient HCID service for England. This will enable the NHS to deliver care safely and effectively for a wider range of known and unknown HCIDs.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-26T15:28:03.58Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868348/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868348/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868348/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-21","Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of recent WHO reports on Disease X.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","133568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868349","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-28","<p>National statistics on low income are set out in the annual &quot;Households below Average Income&quot; publication. The number of children in absolute low income is not available for families where the parent has indefinite leave to remain in this publication. Estimates for 2016/17 show that there were 300,000 fewer children in absolute low income than in 2010 - a record low.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-28T15:44:55.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868349/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868349/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868349/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-21","National Insurance: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate her Department has made of the number of children who are living in families where the parent has indefinite leave to remain but has yet to receive a National Insurance number; and how many of those children are living in absolute poverty.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","133569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868350","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-28","<p>DWP are unaware of the numbers of asylum seekers who have been granted indefinite leave to remain in the UK however when, the Home Office grant the application for indefinite leave they forward the personal details to NINo operations and a NINo is allocated within 48 hours.</p><p> </p><p>From 15 January 2018 this process is applicable to the principle family member and any adult dependants aged 16 or over in the refugees family. With the NINo being allocated within 48 hours this facilitates the smooth transition from asylum support to mainstream benefits.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-28T15:44:53.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868350/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868350/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868350/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-21","National Insurance: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people who have indefinite leave to remain and have reached the end of their eligibility for asylum support are waiting to receive a national insurance number.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","133570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868351","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-29","<p>The Government is investing nearly £1.5bn‎ between April 2015 and March 2021 in one of the most comprehensive global programmes of support for electric vehicles, with grants available for new plug in cars, vans, lorries, buses, taxis and motorcycles, and schemes to support charging point infrastructure at homes and workplaces and on residential streets. The Government’s forthcoming zero emission road transport strategy, which will be published after the local elections, will set out its plans to support the UK transition to zero emission vehicles. There is a developing market for second hand electric vehicles. Used electric vehicle motorists are able to take advantage of the favourable tax regime the Government has put in place and local initiatives such as free parking, as well as the Government’s grant schemes to assist with the cost of installing chargepoints.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-29T10:45:06.59Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868351/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868351/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868351/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-21","Electric Vehicles","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what incentives the Government plans to provide for the purchase of electric cars; and what step his Department plans to take to stimulate the used electric car market.","false","Biography information for James Frith","Bury North","James Frith","133571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868352","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-28","<p>No compensation will be paid to Govia Thameslink Railway (GTR). Some of the money will be used to pay for additional costs incurred by GTR as a result of the disruption to passengers, for example bus replacement services – according to usual industry processes. For other franchises, some compensation would normally be paid to franchisees to reflect the loss of revenue resulting from the engineering work impact. Again this is part of standard industry practice. For the Thameslink, Southern and Great Northern (TSGN) franchise, as the Department for Transport takes revenue risk, this compensation will not be paid to GTR.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2018-03-28T14:41:25.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868352/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868352/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868352/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868352/answer/previousversion/49836","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-21","Govia Thameslink Railway: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, how much of the £300 million allocated by his Department to Network Rail for improvement works on the Southern and Thameslink networks will be paid to Govia Thameslink Railway in compensation for disruption during those works.","false","Biography information for Sarah Jones","Croydon Central","Sarah Jones","133572"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868353","Department for Education","false","2018-03-26","<p>The duty to publish a report is for the Social Mobility Commission. To enable the Social Mobility Commission to report on the progress made towards improving social mobility, the department has begun the recruitment process for a new Chair and we will look to recruit new Commissioners in due course, following standard Public Appointment procedures.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-26T16:43:32.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868353/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868353/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868353/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-21","Social Mobility Commission: Publications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, who has the duty to publish a report on behalf of the Social Mobility Commission for each financial year in the absence of any commissioners; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lyn Brown","West Ham","Lyn Brown","133573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868354","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-27","<p>My Rt Hon. Friend the Secretary of State for International Trade has spoken on several occasions to the Commerce Secretary and to the US Trade Representative about the investigation, including when he travelled to Washington last week for face-to-face meetings with both to make the case for the UK as part of the EU.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2018-03-27T16:09:43.447Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868354/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868354/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868354/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868354/answer/previousversion/49843","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-21","Import Duties: USA","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what information he has received from the US Administration on the criteria by which requests for exemptions from the tariffs on steel and aluminium imports will be evaluated.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","133574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868355","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-28","<p>We are working with fellow member states to negotiate the communiqué for next month's Commonwealth Heads of Government. We do not comment on those negotiations while they are underway. The UK considers freedom of religion and belief to be one of the Commonwealth's core values.</p><p>Encouraging member states to uphold the values and principles enshrined in the Commonwealth Charter – which include freedom of religion as well as democracy, freedom of expression, the rule of law and opposition to all forms of discrimination – will be an important part of April's summit.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-28T14:29:40.207Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868355/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868355/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868355/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-21","Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting: Religious Freedom","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps he is taking to ensure that the right to freedom of religion and belief will (a) be discussed at the Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting and (b) included in the Commonwealth Heads of Government Joint Communiqué.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","133575"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868356","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-28","<p>The review engaged with medical experts, stakeholders and employers in expert case analysis and group descriptor analysis.</p><p> </p><p>Details of how the review was conducted and what evidence was taken into account before the group proposed descriptors for the Work Capability Assessment can be found in the published report:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110601194444/http:/www.dwp.gov.uk/docs/work-capability-assessment-review.pdf" target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20110601194444/http://www.dwp.gov.uk/docs/work-capability-assessment-review.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>In November 2010, Professor Malcolm Harrington published his Independent Review of the Work Capability Assessment, the first of five annual Independent Reviews.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-03-28T15:44:50.857Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868356/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868356/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868356/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-21","Work Capability Assessment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to her Department's internal review in 2009 of the descriptors in the work capability assessment, if she will publish the evidential basis for the choice of descriptors used in the work capability assessment; and  whether her Department (a) consulted external bodies and (b) commissioned independent research when deciding on those descriptors.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","133576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868357","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-28","<p>We do not breakdown the businesses signed-up up to Disability Confident by Private / Public sector. The figures as at 23 March 2018 are:</p><p> </p><ul><li><p>5, 964 Disability Confident businesses</p></li></ul><p> </p><ul><ul><li><p>3,217 Disability Confident Committed employers (level 1)</p></li><li><p>2,630 Disability Confident Employers (level 2)</p></li><li><p>117 Disability Confident Leaders (level 3)</p></li></ul></ul><p> </p><p>A full list is published on the Disability Confident website at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/disability-confident-employers-that-have-signed-up" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/disability-confident-employers-that-have-signed-up</a>. This is updated on a regular basis.</p><p> </p><p>We are constantly looking at ways to improve Disability Confident and have introduced a Professional Advisers Group (PAG). The PAG works with my officials to evaluate the impact of aspects of the scheme and suggest amendments and developments where appropriate. For example, we have introduced a Specialist Thematic approach, which has so far delivered two programmes focused on mental health and workplace adjustments. These programmes have been evaluated by the PAG, and suggested improvements will be incorporated into further specialist themed programmes.</p><p> </p><p>The PAG has also considered the impact of the scheme itself, and has recommended a number of changes which have been incorporated and disseminated recently.</p><p>We have also appointed a Disability Confident Business Leaders Group (BLG), comprising senior leaders from significant British businesses across all sectors. The BLG is helping to increase engagement with employers, promoting the business benefits of disability employment, and working with my officials to identify any changes or developments that will improve the effectiveness of the scheme.</p><p>We plan to conduct a more formal and robust evaluation of the Disability Confident scheme, and will be discussing this with the PAG, BLG, and other key stakeholders.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2018-03-28T15:44:49.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868357/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868357/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868357/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-21","Employment: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many private sector organisations hold level (a) one, (b) two and (c) three accreditation under the disability confident scheme; and whether there has been an independent evaluation of the effectiveness of that scheme.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","133577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868358","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-27","<p>As stated in the UK <em>Technical Note on “Other Separation Issues”</em> – where the UK does not have existing domestic legislation to protect certain types of rights, it will establish new schemes. This will preserve the full scope of the unregistered Community design right in the UK</p><p> </p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-03-27T11:57:55.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868358/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868358/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868358/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-21","Intellectual Property: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, if the Government will ensure that the same level of rights under the EU unregistered designs regime is maintained in the UK after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Marsha De Cordova","Battersea","Marsha De Cordova","133578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868359","Department for International Trade","false","2018-03-27","<p>The decision to initiate a safeguards investigation is the responsibility of the European Commission. We are working closely with the European Commission and EU Member States on a response to the proposed US actions.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","133705","2018-03-27T10:29:29.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868359/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868359/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868359/answer","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868359/answer/previousversion/49850","Biography information for Greg Hands","202","International Trade","International Trade","2018-03-21","Import Duties: EU Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what discussions he has had with his counterparts in EU Member States on the potential merits of introducing safeguarding tariffs against cheap steel and aluminium imports redirected from the United States.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","133579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868360","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Department is not responsible for collecting data on the number of applications to study nursing degree courses.</p><p> </p><p>The Universities and Colleges Admissions Service publishes data on the number of applications to full-time undergraduate courses.</p><p> </p><p>Further information and links to 2017 and 2018 application cycle data are available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.ucas.com/corporate/data-and-analysis" target="_blank">https://www.ucas.com/corporate/data-and-analysis</a></p>","North East Cambridgeshire","Stephen Barclay",,"2018-03-26T15:50:31.173Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868360/answer","Biography information for Stephen Barclay","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868360/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868360/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-21","Nurses: Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what information his Department holds on the number of applications to university nursing courses in England in the 2018 undergraduate cycle (a) by nursing discipline and (b) in each region of the country.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","133580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868361","Treasury","false","2018-03-29","<p>The concept of a “bespoke tax agreement” does not exist in law. HMRC deals with individual and corporate taxpayers in accordance with its published Litigation and Settlement Strategy:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/655344/HMRC_Resolving_tax_disputes.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/655344/HMRC_Resolving_tax_disputes.pdf </a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","133582","2018-03-29T11:05:22.377Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868361/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868361/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868361/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-21","Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of bespoke tax agreements between the Government and UK companies on the total tax take in the UK.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","133581"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868362","Treasury","false","2018-03-29","<p>The concept of a “bespoke tax agreement” does not exist in law. HMRC deals with individual and corporate taxpayers in accordance with its published Litigation and Settlement Strategy:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/655344/HMRC_Resolving_tax_disputes.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/655344/HMRC_Resolving_tax_disputes.pdf </a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","133581","2018-03-29T11:05:22.44Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868362/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868362/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868362/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-21","Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what is the total number of companies that have entered into a bespoke tax agreement with the UK in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","133582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868363","Treasury","false","2018-03-28","<p>There are currently a number of ways to claim tax relief, depending on the tax involved and the tax status of the customer. As HM Revenue and Customs is transforming its services digitally, it is exploring opportunities to streamline and improve the ways its customers can claim the tax reliefs that Parliament intends.</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-28T10:29:48.6Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868363/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868363/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868363/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-21","Tax Allowances","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans his Department has to review current avenues for claiming tax relief.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","133583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868364","Department for International Development","false","2018-03-27","<p>Aid delivered by road by trusted humanitarian partners is by far the most effective way to meet needs in Syria and to ensure that it reaches those most in need. We have, however, examined all options as part of our determination to do everything we can to alleviate the suffering of the Syrian people.</p><p> </p><p>Airdrops, manned or using drones, are not capable of meeting either the scale of needs or delivering many of the kinds of aid that could address the priority needs that we see in Syria (e.g. safe drinking water, health support). Furthermore, we judge that such an operation would carry a high level of risk because the consent is needed of those who control the airspace and those on the ground that could threaten aircraft. There is nothing to suggest that the Assad regime would provide such consent, given that it continues to use the denial of aid as a weapon of war.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-27T16:35:42.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868364/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868364/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868364/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2018-03-21","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment has his Department has made of the feasability of conducting airdrops of humanitarian aid in Syria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","133584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868365","Treasury","false","2018-03-26","<p>Under the Financial Services and Markets Act 2000, any firm (whether a business, a not-for-profit or a sole trader) carrying out a regulated activity must be authorised or registered by the FCA, unless they are exempt. It is a criminal offence to carry out regulated activities if a firm is not authorised or exempt.</p><p> </p><p>All FCA regulated firms must adhere to the Principles for Businesses, as set out in the FCA Handbook.</p>","Salisbury","John Glen",,"2018-03-26T13:05:38.18Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868365/answer","Biography information for John Glen","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868365/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868365/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-21","Financial Services: Regulation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether paragraph 2.1 of the Financial Conduct Authority's (FCA) Principles for Business applies to (a) all firms authorised by the FCA and (b) firms engaged in regulated activities which are not authorised by the FCA.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","133585"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868366","Cabinet Office","false","2018-04-11","<p>It is the policy of<a href="http://gov.uk/" target="_blank"> GOV.UK</a> Verify not to track individual users, including the services which they access. Building a model that respects privacy is essential if users are to place and maintain their trust in identity assurance.</p><p>PQ 8509 relates to verified user identities. ‘Success’ in the context of verified user identities is measured as the percentage of people with a verified identity who are then ‘matched’ with the departmental service they are attempting to access. The matching rates vary for each service depending on the data held and the matching needs of that service. For some services, for example Universal Credit, it is required that the user must match an existing record within the service. This is not required for all services, as the user may not previously have accessed that service, for example claiming for redundancy payments.</p><p> </p>","Hertsmere","Oliver Dowden","133409 ; 133587 ; 133588 ; 133589 ; 133590 ; 133591 ; 133592 ; 133593 ; 133595 ; 133596 ; 133597 ; 133598 ; 133599 ; 133600 ; 133601","2018-04-11T11:21:48.517Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868366/answer","Biography information for Oliver Dowden","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868366/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/868366/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2018-03-21","Electronic Government: Proof of Identity","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, pursuant to the Answer of 13 September 2017 to Question 8509 on Electronic Government: Proof of Identity, what the average success rate for people using Gov.UK Verify for Vehicle Operator Licensing has been in each month since July 2016.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","133586"
