ernment, pursuant to the Answer of 15 March 2018 to Question 131885 on Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: procurement, if he will provide details of the value of each contractor and the name of the contractor for each contract referred to.","false","Biography information for Jon Trickett","Hemsworth","Jon Trickett","133353"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867379","Department for Education","false","2018-03-26","<p>Local authorities (LAs) are under a statutory duty to ensure that there are sufficient schools in their area to meet the needs of the local population. This includes reviewing provision where populations have grown or declined. Where LAs have identified surplus capacity and/or the need to reorganise schools in their area, they have the power to close all categories of maintained school.</p><p>The LA must follow a well established statutory process when considering the closure of a school. This process includes a consultation period to allow those affected by the proposal to submit their views and comments.</p><p>Northumberland County Council is currently carrying out an informal consultation to seek views on a number of proposed options for the reorganisation of education provision in the west of the county.</p><p>Ultimately, it is the LA who makes the decision about whether or not to close a school, and the department has no direct role in the decision-making process.</p>","Stratford-on-Avon","Nadhim Zahawi",,"2018-03-26T16:51:56.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867379/answer","Biography information for Nadhim Zahawi","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867379/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867379/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-20","Schools: Northumberland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what assessment he has made of the effect of proposals for school closures in West Northumberland on the provision of schooling in that area.","false","Biography information for Mike Kane","Wythenshawe and Sale East","Mike Kane","133354"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867380","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-28","<p>£310m has been allocated to Defra. This will support ongoing work to ensure a successful EU exit across Defra’s portfolio, from agriculture to the environment, including:</p><ul><li><p>Developing new IT systems to maintain smooth trade in agri-foods and chemicals, and supporting the associated trade negotiations;</p></li><li><p>Ensuring that the UK has a robust environmental regulatory framework after exit;</p></li><li><p>Developing the Government’s approach to farming and fisheries.</p><p> </p></li></ul><p>As with all Reserve funding, finalised allocations will be confirmed at Supplementary Estimates 2018-19 in early 2019.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-28T17:21:44.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867380/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867380/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867380/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-20","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs: Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, pursuant to the Written Statement of 13 March 2018, Spring Statement, HCWS 540, if he will publish a list of where the £310 million in EU exit funding for his Department will be allocated.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","133355"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867381","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-28","<p>Claimants whose health condition remains unchanged and who move from Employment and Support Allowance to Universal Credit, following a fit for work decision that is subsequently overturned, will have their Universal Credit assessed on the basis of having limited capability for work or limited capability for work and work-related activity.</p><p> </p><p>In these circumstances claimants will also be paid any arrears of Employment and Support Allowance that are due up until their claim for Universal Credit.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2018-03-28T14:17:21.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867381/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867381/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867381/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-20","Employment and Support Allowance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if she will ensure that claimants who are moved on to universal credit when employment and support allowance is withdrawn after an assessment and who subsequently get that decision overturned on appeal can claim employment and support allowance at their previous rate.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","133356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867382","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Foreign Secretary was delighted to address delegates to the Commonwealth Parliamentarians' Forum during their recent visit to London. He has received copies of the forum outputs, including: the Declaration of the First Commonwealth Parliamentarians Forum; The Youth Delegate Declaration; and a letter from delegates calling for the creation of a Commonwealth Climate Change Council at April's Heads of Government Meeting.</p><p>Mitigating the effects of climate change, especially as it affects small island states, will be one of the main policy areas leaders will discuss at the summit. Issues affecting the Commonwealth's young population will also feature prominently during the summit, with one of the four official forums at the start of the week dedicated to Youth.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2018-03-28T13:17:51.753Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867382/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867382/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867382/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2018-03-20","Commonwealth Heads of Government Meeting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the outputs published from the Commonwealth Parliamentarians’ Forum hosted by the Commonwealth Parliamentary Association from 26 February to 1 March 2018, whether he plans to take steps in response to those outputs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for James Duddridge","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge","133357"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867383","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-26","<p>The United Kingdom National Screening Committee (UK NSC) makes recommendations to introduce a new screening programme based on robust peer reviewed evidence. This process was recognised by the House of Commons Science and Technology Committee Inquiry into Health Screening, which supported the idea that the evidential barrier should remain high because of the potential for screening to do harm. Further information is available here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmsctech/244/24409.htm" target="_blank">https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201415/cmselect/cmsctech/244/24409.htm</a></p><p> </p><p>In 2015, the UK NSC did not recommend screening to prevent Sudden Cardiac Death (SCD) in 12 to 39 year olds. This was due to the epidemiology of the condition not being fully understood a lack of published peer reviewed evidence to correctly identify the number of people affected and issues around the test. Further information on UK NSC’s recommendation can be found here:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://legacyscreening.phe.org.uk/suddencardiacdeath" target="_blank">https://legacyscreening.phe.org.uk/suddencardiacdeath</a></p><p> </p><p>The UK NSC will be reviewing SCD in 2018/19.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-26T15:06:47.607Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867383/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867383/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867383/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-20","Heart Diseases: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of the evidential basis for the decision of the UK National Screening Committee in 2015 not to recommend screening to prevent sudden cardiac death in 12 to 39-year-olds.","false","Biography information for Priti Patel","Witham","Priti Patel","133358"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867384","Ministry of Defence","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Ministry of Defence considers that the current arrangements are an improvement over those previously in place. However, accurate collection of income tax from our deployed Reservists requires their civilian employers to follow the guidance issued online at: https://www.gov.uk/employee-reservist.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2018-03-26T15:13:36.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867384/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867384/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867384/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2018-03-20","Reserve Forces: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, with reference to the Answer of 3 April 2017 to Question 69592, on Reserve Forces: Pay, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of the changes to internal tax code procedures for Reservist personnel.","false","Biography information for Gerald Jones","Merthyr Tydfil and Rhymney","Gerald Jones","133359"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867385","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-04-09","<p>The Environment Agency undertook an economic assessment and this has been published in the link below. It is their view that the increase in permit costs is small in comparison to other start-up costs.</p><p> </p><p>https://www.gov.uk/government/consultations/environment-agency-charge-proposals-from-april-2018</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-04-09T16:12:33.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867385/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867385/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867385/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-20","Poultry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential effect on the viability of poultry businesses of the increase in permit charges for intensive poultry farming in April 2018.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","133360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867386","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Environment Agency confirmed on 21 March 2018 that the new charges would come into effect from 1 April 2018. This decision was taken following consideration of comments from charge payers. Their consultation response document is available online and sets out where proposals have been adjusted to take consultation feedback into account, including the decision not to delay implementation.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2018-03-28T13:10:29.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867386/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867386/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867386/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-20","Poultry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether his Department has had discussions with the Environment Agency on delaying the planned increase in permit charges for intensive poultry farming until April 2019; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Bill Wiggin","North Herefordshire","Bill Wiggin","133361"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867387","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Department has made no assessment itself. However, in developing its technology appraisal guidance, the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence, takes into account all the costs and savings associated with the treatment compared with existing clinical practice.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-27T14:32:34.33Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867387/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867387/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867387/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-20","Orkambi","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, whether his Department has made an assessment of the potential reduction in hospital admissions for people with cystic fibrosis were Orkambi to be made available on the NHS.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","133362"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867388","Treasury","false","2018-03-26","<p>The UK has complied with the requirements of the European Union Joint Transfer Pricing Forum and provided statistics on the number of Advance Pricing Agreements in force.</p><p>The statistics are available at: <a href="https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/business/company-tax/transfer-pricing-eu-context/joint-transfer-pricing-forum_en" target="_blank">https://ec.europa.eu/taxation_customs/business/company-tax/transfer-pricing-eu-context/joint-transfer-pricing-forum_en</a></p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-26T13:06:42.347Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867388/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867388/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867388/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-20","Advance Pricing Agreements","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for what reasons the Government has not complied with the requirements of the European Union Joint Transfer Pricing Forum in providing statistics on the number of Advance Pricing Agreements in force for the fifth consecutive year.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","133363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867389","Treasury","false","2018-03-28","<p>HMRC is reshaping to become a modern, flexible and cost-effective organisation, occupying fewer offices, and able to maximise revenue yield through increased compliance, greater capacity for digital business and by providing better, more personal services for its customers. Since commencement of HMRC’s Building Our Future Locations programme, to date, the number of confirmed related exits is 1,387. This equates to 2.1% of HMRC’s current workforce of 66,141</p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride",,"2018-03-28T16:36:40.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867389/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867389/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867389/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-20","Revenue and Customs: Resignations","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many staff are estimated to have left HMRC as a result of the Government’s Building Our Future programme to date.","false","Biography information for Anneliese Dodds","Oxford East","Anneliese Dodds","133364"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867390","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Government recognises the importance of public toilets as a valuable community amenity and has encouraged local authorities to keep them open to the public. We will keep under review the need for any further action to support local authorities in doing so.</p>","Richmond (Yorks)","Rishi Sunak",,"2018-03-26T16:52:10.543Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867390/answer","Biography information for Rishi Sunak","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867390/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867390/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2018-03-20","Public Lavatories: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, if he will introduce discretionary business rate relief for public toilets.","false","Biography information for Scott Mann","North Cornwall","Scott Mann","133365"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867391","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>We have no plans to further extend the SMETS1 end date.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:20:44.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867391/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867391/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867391/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Energy: Meters","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what his policy is on a further extension of the smart meter SMETS1 end date.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133366"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867392","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Clean Growth Strategy set out the Government’s new direction on carbon capture, usage and storage (CCUS). This included a commitment to review the delivery and investment frameworks for CCUS. This is now underway and a report examining the business models for transporting and storing carbon dioxide was published in January 2018[1].</p><p>Further to this, the CCUS Cost Challenge Taskforce, established in February 2018 and comprising over forty industry representatives, will also consider possible business models for CCUS. The Taskforce will deliver their report by summer 2018.</p><p><em><sup><strong><sup>[1]</sup></strong></sup></em> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/guidance/uk-carbon-capture-and-storage-government-funding-and-support" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/guidance/uk-carbon-capture-and-storage-government-funding-and-support</em></a></p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:25:07.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867392/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867392/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867392/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what progress he has made on finding a business model for carbon capture storage and utilisation which goes beyond enhanced oil recovery to date.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133367"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867393","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>Officials in the Department hold regular discussions with the Committee on Climate Change, on subjects including carbon capture, usage and storage (CCUS).</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:22:00.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867393/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867393/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867393/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Committee on Climate Change on the advancement of carbon capture storage and utilisation.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133368"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867394","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>My noble Friend the Parliamentary Under Secretary of State (Lord Henley) responded in a letter to Lord Oxburgh on 15 January 2018 on the recommendations made in the Parliamentary Advisory Group’s report on carbon capture and storage. A copy of the letter was deposited in the Library of the House and is available at:</p><p><a href="http://data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2018-0025/Lord_Oxburgh_KBb_Carbon_Capture_Usage_and_Storage.pdf" target="_blank">http://data.parliament.uk/DepositedPapers/Files/DEP2018-0025/Lord_Oxburgh_KBb_Carbon_Capture_Usage_and_Storage.pdf</a></p><p>As set out in Lord Henley’s letter, the recommendations made in the report have been considered in the development of our new approach to CCUS, as set out in the Clean Growth Strategy, and will continue to be a consideration in the shaping our ongoing work.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:21:02.69Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867394/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867394/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867394/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Carbon Capture and Storage","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when the Government plans to respond to the Oxburgh Report on carbon capture storage and utilisation.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133369"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867395","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Renewable Heat Incentive (RHI) has always been focussed on low carbon heating. The government is reforming the RHI to ensure it focusses better on long-term decarbonisation – through technologies such as biomethane and heat pumps - and offers better value for money. These reforms were set out in December 2016 in the response to the consultation ‘The Renewable Heat Incentive: A Reformed and Refocused scheme’. The first stage of the reforms were enacted in September 2017 and further regulations are currently in Parliament.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:28:23.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867395/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867395/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867395/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he has plans to re-target the Renewable Heat Incentive towards lower carbon forms of heating; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133370"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867396","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>BEIS ministers and officials are in regular contact with the Committee on Climate Change on a range of issues including the contribution of low carbon heat from the Renewable Heat Incentive towards the UK’s carbon budgets.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:27:12.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867396/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867396/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867396/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Renewable Heat Incentive Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what discussions he has had with the Committee on Climate Change on re-targeting the Renewable Heat Incentive towards lower carbon forms of heating.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133371"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867397","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>The Heat Metering and Billing Regulations 2014 require heat suppliers to notify the Secretary of State if they have an existing heat network and how it is complying with the Regulations. An initial set of aggregated statistics on a small sample of notification data that had been quality assured were published in February 2017 and can be found <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/593899/Copy_of_Final_HMBR_Publication_Feb_2017.xlsx" target="_blank">here.</a> Summary statistics on a much larger portion of quality assured data are planned to be released as part of Energy Trends on 29 March 2018. There are no plans to establish a public database containing details of individual existing UK heat networks.</p><p> </p><p>Additionally, the Heat Networks Delivery Unit has recently started to publish quarterly reports on heat networks projects in the development pipeline, which will act as public database of potential future heat networks. These reports can be found at this <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/hndu-pipeline" target="_blank">link</a>.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:21:38.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867397/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867397/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867397/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","District Heating","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to establish a public database of UK heat networks; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","133372"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867398","Department for Education","false","2018-03-28","<p>The department uses the definition and data published by the Higher Education Statistics Agency (HESA). HESA generally classes undergraduates as young if they are under 21 years of age on entry, and mature if they are 21 or over. Postgraduates are classed as young if they are under 25 years of age on entry, and mature if they are 25 or over.</p><p> </p><p>The term “full-time” is used by HESA to refer to any student required to attend a higher education provider for at least 24 weeks within the year of study and to undertake tuition, study or work experience for an average of at least 21 hours per week. It also includes those enrolled on any sandwich course.</p><p> </p><p>More information on the definitions that HESA uses can be found at: <a href="https://www.hesa.ac.uk/support/definitions/students" target="_blank">https://www.hesa.ac.uk/support/definitions/students</a>.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2018-03-28T15:55:08.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867398/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867398/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867398/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2018-03-20","Mature Students","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what definition his Department uses for a mature (a) full-time student and (b) part-time student.","false","Biography information for Angela Rayner","Ashton-under-Lyne","Angela Rayner","133373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867399","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-26","<p>The table below shows how many young people (under 18) are in each Young Offender Institution (YOI) in England and Wales:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Year ending March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Under 18 YOI</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>2018<sup>(1)</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cookham Wood</p></td><td><p>135</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>144</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feltham</p></td><td><p>129</p></td><td><p>124</p></td><td><p>133</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parc</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Werrington</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>95</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wetherby</p></td><td><p>242</p></td><td><p>225</p></td><td><p>219</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>656</p></td><td><p>630</p></td><td><p>632</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ul><li>There data are provisional. The 2017/18 figures will be finalised in the 2017/18 <em>Youth Justice Statistics </em>which will be published in January 2019. The 2017/18 figures are based on 10 monthly snapshots (Apr-17 to Jan-18) only.</li><li>These figures are averages of 12 monthly snapshots of the custodial population in the secure estate for children and young people, taken on the last Friday of the month or first Friday of the following month, depending on which is nearer to the actual month end.</li><li>These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing and can be subject to change over time.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The table below shows how many young adults (18 -20 years old) are in each YOI in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>18 - 21 dedicated YOIs</p></td><td><p>As at 31 December 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aylesbury</p></td><td><p>313</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cookham Wood</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Deerbolt</p></td><td><p>315</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feltham</p></td><td><p>325</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Werrington</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wetherby</p></td><td><p>28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>1,021</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ul><li>The data in the table is drawn from a different administrative IT system. Like any large scale recording system, is subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</li><li>There are a number of young adults (turned 18) in the under 18 YOIs who are awaiting transition to the adult estate.</li></ul><p> </p><p>In the Children and Young People Secure Estate (under 18s), speech and language therapy is integrated into the overall commissioning of health services. We are committed to supporting all young offenders in custody and provide a range of services for children with special educational needs. Within the under 18 YOIs, each establishment has a Special Educational Needs co-ordinator (SENCO) and a team of LSA’s (Learning Support Assistants) to support the young people. The Senco keeps a register of young people with Special Educational Needs and Disabilities, including their individual needs, and shares the information with the establishment. All young people have Individual Learning Plans set up and reviewed by the education provider, regardless of whether they receive mainstream or outreach education. We do not collect data centrally relating to speech, language or communication needs.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","133375","2018-03-26T15:30:28.303Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867399/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867399/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867399/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-20","Young Offenders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many young offenders aged (a) 15-17 and (b) 18-20 years old are in each young offenders institution in England and Wales; and how many in each such age group at each such institution are identified as having speech, language or communications needs.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","133374"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867400","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-26","<p>The table below shows how many young people (under 18) are in each Young Offender Institution (YOI) in England and Wales:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td colspan="3"><p>Year ending March</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Under 18 YOI</p></td><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>2018<sup>(1)</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cookham Wood</p></td><td><p>135</p></td><td><p>136</p></td><td><p>144</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feltham</p></td><td><p>129</p></td><td><p>124</p></td><td><p>133</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parc</p></td><td><p>49</p></td><td><p>45</p></td><td><p>42</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Werrington</p></td><td><p>101</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>95</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wetherby</p></td><td><p>242</p></td><td><p>225</p></td><td><p>219</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>656</p></td><td><p>630</p></td><td><p>632</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ul><li>There data are provisional. The 2017/18 figures will be finalised in the 2017/18 <em>Youth Justice Statistics </em>which will be published in January 2019. The 2017/18 figures are based on 10 monthly snapshots (Apr-17 to Jan-18) only.</li><li>These figures are averages of 12 monthly snapshots of the custodial population in the secure estate for children and young people, taken on the last Friday of the month or first Friday of the following month, depending on which is nearer to the actual month end.</li><li>These figures have been drawn from administrative IT systems which, as with any large scale recording system, are subject to possible errors with data entry and processing and can be subject to change over time.</li></ul><p> </p><p>The table below shows how many young adults (18 -20 years old) are in each YOI in England and Wales.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>18 - 21 dedicated YOIs</p></td><td><p>As at 31 December 2017</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Aylesbury</p></td><td><p>313</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Cookham Wood</p></td><td><p>29</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Deerbolt</p></td><td><p>315</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Feltham</p></td><td><p>325</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Werrington</p></td><td><p>11</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Wetherby</p></td><td><p>28</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total</p></td><td><p>1,021</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ul><li>The data in the table is drawn from a different administrative IT system. Like any large scale recording system, is subject to possible errors with data entry and processing.</li><li>There are a number of young adults (turned 18) in the under 18 YOIs who are awaiting transition to the adult estate.</li></ul><p> </p><p>In the Children and Young People Secure Estate (under 18s), speech and language therapy is integrated into the overall commissioning of health services. We are committed to supporting all young offenders in custody and provide a range of services for children with special educational needs. Within the under 18 YOIs, each establishment has a Special Educational Needs co-ordinator (SENCO) and a team of LSA’s (Learning Support Assistants) to support the young people. The Senco keeps a register of young people with Special Educational Needs and Disabilities, including their individual needs, and shares the information with the establishment. All young people have Individual Learning Plans set up and reviewed by the education provider, regardless of whether they receive mainstream or outreach education. We do not collect data centrally relating to speech, language or communication needs.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","133374","2018-03-26T15:30:28.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867400/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867400/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867400/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-20","Young Offender Institutions: Speech and Language Therapy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) full-time and (b part-ime speech and language therapists are employed to provide services for each young offenders institution in England and Wales; and how many hours of service provision are scheduled at each such institution each week.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","133375"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867401","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-26","<p>(a) Data on the number and types of incidents that occur in under-18 young offender institutions is published in the quarterly Safety in Custody bulletin. This does not include a single category of ‘violent incidents’. The latest published figures for under-18 Young Offender Institutions covers the years 2007 to Dec 2017 and is contained in the link below. The next quarterly figures will be published in April 2018.</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-september-2017" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/safety-in-custody-quarterly-update-to-september-2017</a></p><p> </p><p>(b) The table below shows the latest data available (2016) on the number of assaults and serious assaults on staff within the under 18 Young Offender Institutions. Data for 2017 will be published in April 2018.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p>Cookham Wood</p></td><td><p>Feltham</p></td><td><p>Parc</p></td><td><p>Werrington</p></td><td><p>Wetherby</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No of Assaults on staff</p></td><td><p>126</p></td><td><p>182</p></td><td><p>245</p></td><td><p>138</p></td><td><p>97</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>No of serious assaults on staff</p></td><td><p>9</p></td><td><p>32</p></td><td><p>21</p></td><td><p>10</p></td><td><p>23</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><em>Note : An assault is classified as serious if it : is a sexual assault, results in detention in outside hospital as an inpatient, requires medical treatment for concussion or internal injuries or </em><em>the injury is a fracture, scald or burn, stabbing, crushing, extensive or multiple bruising, black eye, broken nose, lost or broken tooth, cuts requiring suturing or similar treatment, bites, or temporary or permanent blindness.</em></p><p> </p><p><em>Data for Feltham and Parc includes young adults as they are split sites</em><em>.</em></p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2018-03-26T15:20:19.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867401/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867401/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867401/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-20","Young Offender Institutions: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many (a) violent incidents and (b) assaults on prison staff have been recorded for each young offenders institution in England and Wales in the last twelve months.","false","Biography information for Seema Malhotra","Feltham and Heston","Seema Malhotra","133376"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867402","Ministry of Justice","false","2018-03-26","<p>The number of magistrates serving as at 1 April 2017 in England and Wales can be found in the Judicial Diversity Statistics at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/judicial-diversity-statistics-2017--2" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/judicial-diversity-statistics-2017--2</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The information requesting how many of those magistrates currently serving in these areas were serving in March in each of the last five years could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>The number of magistrates serving in England and Wales as at 1 April in the last five years can be found in the Judicial Diversity Statistics Archive at <a href="https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/publications/?filter_type=publication&amp;search=&amp;tax-single-subject=171&amp;tax-single-publication-type=169&amp;tax-single-publication-jurisdiction=-1&amp;date-range-after=&amp;date-range-before" target="_blank">https://www.judiciary.gov.uk/publications/?filter_type=publication&amp;search=&amp;tax-single-subject=171&amp;tax-single-publication-type=169&amp;tax-single-publication-jurisdiction=-1&amp;date-range-after=&amp;date-range-before</a></p><p> </p><p>The number of serving magistrates in England and Wales by (a) ethnic minority and (b) by age category is also available in the public domain and can be accessed via the links provided above.</p><p> </p><p>The published data covers the period up to 1<sup>st</sup> April 2017. We plan to publish data which covers the period up to 1<sup>st</sup> April 2018 in July.</p>","South East Cambridgeshire","Lucy Frazer","133378","2018-03-26T15:01:15.033Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867402/answer","Biography information for Lucy Frazer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867402/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867402/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2018-03-20","Magistrates","1","House of C