"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867404","Treasury","false","2018-03-26","<p>As Vehicle Exercise Duty is a UK wide duty, an English share of VED revenues will be allocated to the road fund. The Scottish Government, Welsh Government and Northern Ireland Executive will receive Barnett consquentials on this funding in the usual way.</p>","South West Norfolk","Elizabeth Truss",,"2018-03-26T13:14:26.003Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867404/answer","Biography information for Elizabeth Truss","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867404/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867404/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-20","Motor Vehicles: Excise Duties","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 5 March 2018 to Question 130335, what proportion of Vehicle Excise Duty is to be allocated to the proposed new Roads Fund from 2020-21 onwards.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","133379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867405","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2018-03-26","<p>Information on savings associated with this policy is provided here: <a href="http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2017/725/impacts" target="_blank">http://www.legislation.gov.uk/uksi/2017/725/impacts</a></p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse",,"2018-03-26T16:23:27.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867405/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867405/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867405/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2018-03-20","Support for Mortgage Interest","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 21 February 2018 to Question 128306, if he will place the evidential basis for the predicted saving of over £160m per year to the taxpayer through the introduction of SMI loans in the Library.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","133380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867406","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Secretary of State has visited a range of countries where he has discussed a variety of issues. Responsibility for the operation of border controls rests with the Home Office.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-03-26T15:54:33.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867406/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867406/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867406/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","Immigration Controls","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which countries he has visited to observe at first hand their border control operations.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","133381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867407","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Secretary of State has met US and Canadian officials through G7 and other meetings, where a range of issues were discussed.</p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-03-26T15:57:40.77Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867407/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867407/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867407/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","Cross Border Cooperation: North America","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when he last met US or Canadian officials to discuss how their cross border customs checks function.","false","Biography information for Alan Brown","Kilmarnock and Loudoun","Alan Brown","133382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867408","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-26","<p>The incumbent operator is working with rolling stock companies to develop different solutions to achieve compliance. Once the industry has developed a preferred solution, it will be considered by the Department, but no decisions have yet been taken.</p><p> </p>","Wealden","Ms Nusrat Ghani",,"2018-03-26T14:27:10.917Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867408/answer","Biography information for Ms Nusrat Ghani","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867408/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867408/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","East Midlands Rail Franchise: Rolling Stock","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps he is taking to ensure that the rolling stock on the East Midlands Trains franchise will be PRM TSI compliant by 2020.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","133383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867409","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Department for Transport appointed Costain and its subcontractor Systra as advisors to the Airport Capacity Programme on 26 February 2018. We have asked them to undertake an early assurance review of Heathrow Airport Limited’s plans for its proposed Northwest Runway scheme. We have requested an interim report by late spring.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-26T14:50:29.907Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867409/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867409/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867409/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the (a) terms of reference and (b) timeframe are for (i) Systra and (ii) Costain to make an assessment of the feasibility of Heathrow Airport’s North West Runway.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","133384"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867410","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-26","<p>In 2015 Heathrow Airport Limited (HAL) submitted a scheme which the Airports Commission assessed would cost £17.6 billion. Following this the Secretary of State set out his ambition for landing charges to remain close to current levels. Subsequently, the Government commissioned the regulator, the Civil Aviation Authority, to oversee and report on the quality of engagement between HAL and its airline customers. This process has proved successful. HAL have reported a reduction in scheme costs by up to £2.5 billion against the scheme they submitted.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-26T16:09:13.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867410/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867410/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867410/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the cost of Heathrow Airport’s North West Runway scheme.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","133385"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867411","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-26","<p>The Planning Act 2008 sets out the circumstances in which any National Policy Statement should be developed, reviewed and amended. The NPS is already clear that the developer should demonstrate that its scheme is cost-efficient and sustainable, and seeks to minimise costs to airlines, passengers and freight owners over its lifetime.</p><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-26T14:23:26.67Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867411/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867411/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867411/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","Heathrow Airport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what contingency plans his Department have made to revise the National Policy Statement in the event of a change to the cost of Heathrow Airport’s North West Runway scheme.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","133386"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867412","Home Office","false","2018-03-29","<p>The Home Office Security &amp; Policing event is organised by the UK Aerospace, Defence &amp; Security (ADS) trade body on behalf of the Home Office. ADS are responsible for the administrative arrangements and hold data on exhibitor and visitor numbers which is not routinely published.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","133388","2018-03-29T13:50:54.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867412/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867412/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867412/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-20","National Security: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many visitors attended the Home Office Security and Policing event in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","133387"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867413","Home Office","false","2018-03-29","<p>The Home Office Security &amp; Policing event is organised by the UK Aerospace, Defence &amp; Security (ADS) trade body on behalf of the Home Office. ADS are responsible for the administrative arrangements and hold data on exhibitor and visitor numbers which is not routinely published.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd","133387","2018-03-29T13:50:54.333Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867413/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867413/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867413/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-20","National Security: Trade Fairs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many exhibitors attended the Home Office Security and Policing event in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Mr Nigel Evans","Ribble Valley","Mr Nigel Evans","133388"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867414","Home Office","false","2018-03-26","<p>Since the repatriation of passport processing in 2014, all decisions relating to UK passport applications made from Ireland have been taken by Her Majesty’s Passport Office in the UK. The information on passport applications processed by the Dublin office before repatriation could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2018-03-26T08:45:37.68Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867414/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867414/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867414/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2018-03-20","Passports: British Embassy Dublin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many passport applications the British embassy in Dublin approved in each of the last 10 years; and of those applications what proportion were (a) for new and (b) to renew passports.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","133389"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867415","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2018-03-26","<p>I refer the honourable gentleman to the data within the below linked response provided to the noble Lord Allen of Kensington. Court proceedings data for 2017 is planned for publication in May 2018.</p><p><a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2017-09-08/HL1470/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Lords/2017-09-08/HL1470/</a></p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2018-03-26T17:10:42.197Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867415/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867415/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867415/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2018-03-20","Animal Welfare: Sentencing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many people have been imprisoned for the offence of animal cruelty in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","133390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867416","Treasury","false","2018-03-26","<p>Making Tax Digital (MTD) is designed to enable businesses to meet their tax obligations as simply as possible.</p><p> </p><p>There will be a range of advice and support available to help businesses prepare for MTD for VAT in April 2019. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is working very closely with software providers, businesses, representative bodies and the accountancy profession to raise awareness of MTD and ensure the right support and training is in place to help businesses adapt.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s customer support model, which will guide businesses to the most appropriate help, includes technical support, webchat, YouTube training videos, webinars, helpline and agent and business guides. HMRC will also publish a list of MTD for VAT compatible products on GOV.UK to help businesses make an informed choice of software to meet their needs. A pilot for VAT will start shortly to test the system, including the support model, well ahead of April 2019.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","133392","2018-03-26T13:09:10.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867416/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867416/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867416/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-20","Taxation: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps his Department is taking to make businesses aware of the introduction of the Making Tax Digital system in April 2019.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","133391"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867417","Treasury","false","2018-03-26","<p>Making Tax Digital (MTD) is designed to enable businesses to meet their tax obligations as simply as possible.</p><p> </p><p>There will be a range of advice and support available to help businesses prepare for MTD for VAT in April 2019. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) is working very closely with software providers, businesses, representative bodies and the accountancy profession to raise awareness of MTD and ensure the right support and training is in place to help businesses adapt.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC’s customer support model, which will guide businesses to the most appropriate help, includes technical support, webchat, YouTube training videos, webinars, helpline and agent and business guides. HMRC will also publish a list of MTD for VAT compatible products on GOV.UK to help businesses make an informed choice of software to meet their needs. A pilot for VAT will start shortly to test the system, including the support model, well ahead of April 2019.</p><p> </p>","Central Devon","Mel Stride","133391","2018-03-26T13:09:10.253Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867417/answer","Biography information for Mel Stride","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867417/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867417/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","Treasury","2018-03-20","Taxation: Electronic Government","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what (a) advice and (b) training the Government is making available to businesses to prepare for the roll-out of the Making Tax Digital system.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","133392"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867418","Department for Transport","false","2018-03-29","<p>In the East Midlands, over £3.2 billion of public money has been spent on transport in the last three years, improving connectivity, shortening journey times, reducing congestion, and transporting people, ideas and goods.</p><p> </p><p>Figures are not available at the level of individual counties. However, in Nottinghamshire, recent Government investment includes £371m towards extensions to the Nottingham tram system, £8.5m towards the Hucknall Town Centre Improvement Scheme, and £5m towards maintenance on the A38 and A617 Mansfield Regeneration Route.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2018-03-29T11:17:07.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867418/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867418/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867418/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2018-03-20","Transport: East Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what funding his Department has provided to support transport projects in (a) the East Midlands and (b) Nottinghamshire in the last three years.","false","Biography information for Ben Bradley","Mansfield","Ben Bradley","133393"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867419","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>The potential financial impacts of e-cigarettes on the public purse are not yet fully understood. The evidence base is still evolving on these products, largely because vaping is still relatively new and the health effects may be very long term. Significant savings to the public purse are likely to arise only if smokers switch completely from smoked tobacco. The Government’s Tobacco Control Plan, published in July 2017, estimates that the National Health Service currently spends £2.5 billion on treating smoking-related diseases and Public Health England assess e-cigarettes to be at least 95% less harmful than smoked tobacco. Reduced harm may not translate exactly into proportional costs savings, but superficially this implies that vaping, as an alternative to smoking, may contribute to significant savings.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-27T14:37:44.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867419/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867419/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867419/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-20","Electronic Cigarettes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what estimate he has made of the potential savings to the public purse from the health service encouraging the uptake of e-cigarettes among smokers.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","133394"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867420","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2018-03-27","<p>The Department has been clear that for smokers, quitting smoking completely is the best way to improve health. E-cigarettes are not risk free. However, the evidence is increasingly clear that e-cigarettes are significantly less harmful to health than cigarettes and can help smokers to quit, particularly when combined with support from stop smoking services.</p><p> </p><p>The Government committed Public Health England (PHE), through the Tobacco Control Plan, published in 2017, to include messages about the relative safety of e-cigarettes in their quit smoking campaigns. PHE’s 2017 Stoptober campaign included e-cigarettes among the array of tools that smokers can use to help them quit and, in their New Year smoking health harms campaign, PHE reprised these messages. It is through this consistent messaging that the Government hopes to reverse the harmful, mistaken – and increasingly widespread – belief that vaping is no safer than smoking.</p>","Winchester","Steve Brine",,"2018-03-27T14:42:47.463Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867420/answer","Biography information for Steve Brine","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867420/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867420/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2018-03-20","Electronic Cigarettes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what steps his Department is taking to encourage smokers to give up by promoting the use of e-cigarettes.","false","Biography information for Julian Sturdy","York Outer","Julian Sturdy","133395"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867421","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>The recent consultation on the domestic <em>Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property)(England and Wales) Regulations 2015</em> proposed to introduce a capped landlord funding contribution.</p><p> </p><p>The Department estimates the policy to affect 280,000 properties across England and Wales that will all benefit from some energy efficiency improvements. If the landlord contribution is capped at £2,500 per property, 85,000 homes will reach Energy Performance Certificate band E, whereas if the cap is set at £5,000, 118,000 homes will achieve band E. The remaining properties under both options will receive some energy efficiency improvements but will not achieve band E.</p><p> </p><p>Full details of the policy options under considerations and the complete consultation stage impact assessment are available via the gov.uk consultation hub.</p><p> </p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:22:19.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867421/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867421/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867421/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Housing Improvement: Landlords","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate he has made of the number of people who will benefit from the landlords' liability fund for improving dwellings being set at (a) £2,500 and (b) £5,000.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","133396"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867422","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2018-03-28","<p>(a) There is a large range of cost effective energy efficiency measures households could install in their homes. Each household has its own set of energy requirements. However, so a measure that is cost effective for one household may not be cost effective for another. The recent consultation impact assessment for the revised Private Rental Sector Regulations (see table 3a) shows the types of measures we expect to be installed to improve Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) Band F and G properties to band E[1]. This gives an indication, for each budget cap, of the likely mix of measures we would expect to be a cost effective way to improve the energy performance of homes.</p><p> </p><p>(b) As set out in the Clean Growth Strategy, upgrading the energy performance of homes can lead to significant bill savings for consumers. For example, the annual running costs of an EPC Band C rated home are £270 lower than the average Band D rated home and £650 less than the average Band E home.</p><p> </p><p>[1] <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/669214/PRS_Consultation_stage_IA.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/669214/PRS_Consultation_stage_IA.pdf</a></p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2018-03-28T14:22:24.91Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867422/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867422/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/867422/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2018-03-20","Energy: Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what assessment he has made of the (a) level of further cost-effective energy efficiency measures that could be installed in homes and (b) effect of those measures on the energy bills of those households.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","133397"
